Geometry/Animations or Geometry/Deformations
    ├── MorphTarget
    ├── MeshDeformer        // e.g. wave animation, noise, physics-based
    ├── CurveDeformer
    └── Skeleton            // eventually rigged models
Geometry-specific animations refer to animations that manipulate the form or
shape of a geometry (like a mesh, curve, or surface) over time. These types
of animations are typically more focused on how the geometry itself changes,
rather than how it is positioned, oriented, or transformed within a scene.
Examples of geometry-specific animations include:
    1.  Vertex Manipulation:
        Deforming a mesh, such as bending, stretching, or applying morph targets.
    2.  Curve Animation:
        Changing the shape or parameters of a curve, such as moving control points
        along a spline to alter its shape.
    3.  Material Animations:
        Animating material properties like color, transparency, or texture coordinates
        (though this could technically fall under Texturing).


